// Section 02 — Feelings and Needs
#import "../utils.typ": divider, fleuron-break, section-heading, ref-block, pullquote, callout

#section-heading("II", "Feelings and Needs")

_I feel like you don't care._

Try saying it out loud. Notice that the word _feel_ is doing none of the work the sentence pretends it is. What follows is not a feeling. It is a verdict on another person, served in language gentle enough to be mistaken for an emotional disclosure, when what it actually is, is an accusation.

Welcome to the trap most of us live in for most of our lives.

_I feel attacked. I feel ignored. I feel manipulated. I feel dismissed. I feel like you're not even trying._ None of these are feelings. They are your hypothesis about another person's behavior, smuggled across the border under a feeling's passport. Look at the sentence. Where is your body in it? It isn't. The other person is the entire sentence.

A real feeling lives in the body. Tight chest. Hot face. The cold thing low in the gut. The shoulder creeping up toward your ear. Sad. Scared. Tired. Lit up. Restless. Tender. Furious. Numb. These are yours. They cannot be argued with, because they are not claims. They are weather.

#pullquote[Weather does not require the other person's agreement to exist.]

The pseudo-feeling — _attacked, ignored, dismissed, abandoned, used, disrespected, manipulated, betrayed_ — is a thought wearing a feeling's coat. It carries an accusation. It invites the other person to defend themselves rather than meet you. And here is the part that smarts: you reach for these constructions hardest in the moments when something real is going on inside you. The actual feeling, usually something more vulnerable than righteous, is right there. The pseudo-feeling is the lid you put on it so you don't have to set it on the table.

This is a thing humans do. We do it. You do it. Someone who has been practicing this for thirty years still does it. They just notice it faster.

Think of it as a translation layer. The faux-feelings are still running, still generating output — delivering verdicts about someone else when what the body actually needed was a report from itself. Run the translation before you open your mouth.

