The reason it matters that _attacked_ is not a feeling has nothing to do with grammar. Saying _you attacked me_ puts the entire drama inside the other person's character. They will defend. You will press. The conversation is now about whether or not they are an attacker, and whether or not you are a person who exaggerates. The actual thing — that you are hurt, that something old got touched, that you wanted closeness and got distance instead — never makes it onto the table. The accusation is the lid.

Compare _I feel like you don't care_ to _I am hurt, and I am longing to feel like I matter to you._

The first is a verdict and an invitation to fight. The second is a feeling, a need, and an invitation. The other person can meet it or not. At least there is something in the room to meet.

#divider

Underneath the feeling is the _need_ — one piece of jargon that earns its place here, because there isn't a clean substitute for it.

#callout[In NVC, _needs_ are not the things you want from a particular person on a particular Tuesday. They are the universal stuff every human runs on — the things you cannot stop wanting, no matter who you are or what kind of week you're having.]

Mattering. Being seen. Rest. Belonging. Solitude. A say in your own life. Safety. Contact. Meaning. Play. Contribution. The things that, if you've gone too long without them, the rest of your life starts behaving strangely.

The need is the _why_ beneath the feeling. You feel hollow because something in you is hungry for connection. You feel taut because something in you is fighting for respect — for _mattering_, more honestly. You feel that low buzz of resentment because something in you has been quietly trading its own rest for someone else's comfort and the bill has come due. The other person is, at most, the occasion. They are not the cause and they are not the cure. This sounds, on first read, like a way of letting people off the hook. It is not. It is a way of locating the ache somewhere you can actually do something about it.

